Analysis workflow for pilot study evaluating the effect of personalising treatment dose in aphasia

Sam Harvey, Marcella Carragher, Michael Walsh Dickey, Miranda Rose

May 2022


This document provides a summary of data processing and analyses for a pilot study which evaluated the effect of personalising treatment dose of a lexical retrieval treatment in four people with chronic post-stroke aphasia.


Setup

Load packages

# load packages

library(knitr)
library(here)
library(tidyverse)
library(lme4)
library(readxl)
library(broom.mixed) # contains tidy() - exponentiate GLM model outputs into ORs with CIs
library(magrittr) # contains %>% operator
library(sjPlot) # using tab_model function to tabulate/compare model outputs 
library(ggplot2)
library(ggeffects)
library(gridExtra)
library(kableExtra)


Import, organise, and preview data

#--- Import probe data ---#
probeData <- read_excel(here("data", "p3-6.probeData.xlsx")) %>%
  mutate(dose_code1 = as.factor(dose_code1), # these columns were numbers (not strings), convert manually
         dose_code2 = as.factor(dose_code2),
         phase = as.factor(phase),
         times_treatedV2 = as.factor(times_treatedV2),
         participant = as.factor(participant),
         set = as.factor(set))

#--- Import naming test data ---#
namingTestData <- read_excel(here("data", "p3-6.namingTestData.xlsx")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = time_1_a:time_4, names_to = "time", values_to = "response") %>%
  separate("time", into = c("drop", "time", "baseline_session"), sep = "_") %>%
  mutate_if(is.character, as.factor) %>% # any columns that are strings, make factors
  mutate(doseCode = as.factor(doseCode), # these columns were numbers (not strings), do it manually
    item_num = as.factor(item_num),
    participant = as.factor(participant))

Create data frames
# Create probeData data frames for Analysis 1 - Learning effects

mr.probeData <- probeData %>% filter(participant == 3) # Include only participant 3's data (MR)
ip.probeData <- probeData %>% filter(participant == 4) 
lr.probeData <- probeData %>% filter(participant == 5) 
ts.probeData <- probeData %>% filter(participant == 6) 

# Create namingTestData data frames for Analysis 2 - Maintenance effects
mr.namingTestData <- namingTestData %>% filter(participant == 3) # Include only participant 3's data (MR)
ip.namingTestData <- namingTestData %>% filter(participant == 4)
lr.namingTestData <- namingTestData %>% filter(participant == 5) 
ts.namingTestData <- namingTestData %>% filter(participant == 6)


Visualise data

Plot multiple-baselines charts and pre/post/follow up charts


Example of code used to plot participant MRs multiple-baselines chart

mr.probePlot <- probeData %>%
  filter(participant == 3) %>%
  group_by(set, session, phase) %>%
  summarize(macc = mean(response)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(y = macc, x = session, color = phase)) +
  facet_wrap(~ set, nrow=4, labeller = as_labeller(mr.set_names)) +
  labs(title = "MR", x = "Probe session", y = "Proportional accuracy") +
    geom_point(size = 1, alpha = 0.8) +
    geom_line(size = 0.5, alpha = 0.8) +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1,21,1), limits = c(1,21)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0,1,.25), limits = c(0,1)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#C00000", "#06A11C", "#ED7D31"), name = "Phase", labels = c("Baseline", "Treatment", "Post-treatment")) +
  theme(
    text = element_text(size = 10, family = "Times"),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5), 
    plot.margin = unit(c(0.2,0,0.2,0.1), "cm"),
    legend.position = "NULL",
    panel.background = element_blank(),
    panel.spacing = unit(0, "cm"), 
    panel.grid.major.y = element_line(colour = "#CCCCCC"), 
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank())

Analysis 1: Learning effects throughout treatment


Analysis 1 modelled day-by-day learning effects throughout treatment by estimating item-level naming accuracy after each subsequent treatment day relative to baseline across the three dose conditions and included comparisons with the untreated condition. This approach is analogous to analyses based on visual inspection such as Conservative Dual-Criterion analysis (Fisher et al., 2003) and non-parametric statistical approaches such as Tau-U or Non-Overlap of Pairs (Parker et al., 2011) that attempt to determine whether performance during the treatment phase significantly exceeds performance during the baseline phase.


We used generalised logistic mixed effects models including an ordinal times_treated variable (which increments with each treatment day). Using an ordinal variable avoids the assumption of linearity during treatment, allowing estimation of the difference in the likelihood of a correct response in a naming probe after each treatment day, compared to baseline. We included fixed-effects for item-level (word frequency, phoneme length) characteristics. The random-effects structure included random intercepts by-item. Models including random slopes for fixed effects and interaction terms failed to converge. Models of identical structure were fitted to each participants data separately allowing within-subject estimation of the effect of treatment versus no treatment for each dose condition and comparison of the effect of each dose condition.


m1.mr <- glmer(response ~ word_freq + phon_length + times_treatedV2*dose_code1
               + (1 | item),
               family = 'binomial', 
               data = mr.probeData,
               control = glmerControl(optimizer = "nlminbwrap", optCtrl=list(maxfun=2e4)))


m1.ip <- glmer(response ~ word_freq + phon_length + times_treatedV2*dose_code1
                        + (1 | item),
                        family = 'binomial', 
                        data = ip.probeData,
                        control = glmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa", optCtrl=list(maxfun=1e6)))


m1.lr <- glmer(response ~ word_freq + phon_length + times_treatedV2*dose_code1
               + (1 | item),
               family = 'binomial', 
               data = lr.probeData,
               control = glmerControl(optimizer = "nlminbwrap", optCtrl=list(maxfun=2e4)))


m1.ts <- glmer(response ~ word_freq + phon_length + times_treatedV2*dose_code1
                        + (1 | item),
                        family = 'binomial', 
                        data = ts.probeData,
                        control = glmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa", optCtrl=list(maxfun=1e6)))

Analysis 2: Treatment effects, dose effects, and maintenance of these effects

Analysis 2 modelled treatment response, dose effects, and maintenance of these effects using secondary outcome data from the 298-item picture naming test conducted pre-treatment, immediately post-treatment, and at two follow-up time points. A generalised linear mixed effects model was constructed to test for main effects of dose and time and their interactions, with random intercepts by-item. Models with identical fixed-effects structure were fitted to each participants data separately allowing within-subject estimation of the effect of treatment versus no treatment for each dose condition and comparison of the effect of each dose condition.


m2.mr <- glmer(response ~ Freq + Phon_length + time*doseCode + (1 | item_num), 
                  family = 'binomial', 
                  data = mr.namingTestData,
                  control = glmerControl(optimizer ="bobyqa")) # model converges with these controls
m2.ip <- glmer(response ~ Freq + Phon_length + time*doseCode + (1 | item_num), 
                  family = 'binomial', 
                  data = ip.namingTestData,
                  control = glmerControl(optimizer ="bobyqa")) # model converges with these controls
m2.lr <- glmer(response ~ Freq + Phon_length + time*doseCode + (1 | item_num), 
                  family = 'binomial', 
                  data = lr.namingTestData,
                  control = glmerControl(optimizer ="bobyqa")) # model converges with these controls
m2.ts <- glmer(response ~ Freq + Phon_length + time*doseCode + (1 | item_num), 
                  family = 'binomial', 
                  data = ts.namingTestData,
                  control = glmerControl(optimizer ="bobyqa")) # model converges with these controls

Summary

Each participant responded differently to treatment. Of the four participants, LR demonstrated greatest learning effects during treatment (Analysis 1) and was the only participant to demonstrate maintenance of treatment versus no-treatment gains four weeks following treatment (Analysis 2). MR and IP demonstrated significant learning effects during treatment but no significant improvement or maintenance following treatment. TS did not demonstrate learning effects. In the accompanying manuscript, we examine factors including dose and schedule, cognitive functions such as self-monitoring ability, and language skills such as underlying lexical semantic and phonological processing that may help understand the observed treatment response variability.
